1
00:00:28,988 --> 00:00:32,367
<i>Although each of the world's countries
would like to dispute this fact,</i>

2
00:00:32,450 --> 00:00:33,910
<i>we French know the truth:</i>

3
00:00:33,993 --> 00:00:36,245
<i>The best food in the world
is made in France.</i>

4
00:00:36,329 --> 00:00:38,414
<i>The best food in France
is made in Paris.</i>

5
00:00:38,498 --> 00:00:42,835
<i>And the best food in Paris, some say,
is made by Chef Auguste Gusteau.</i>

6
00:00:43,044 --> 00:00:45,505
<i>Gusteau's restaurant
is the toast of Paris,</i>

7
00:00:45,588 --> 00:00:47,215
<i>booked five months in advance.</i>

8
00:00:47,298 --> 00:00:50,009
<i>And his dazzling ascent to the top
of fine French cuisine</i>

9
00:00:50,134 --> 00:00:52,512
<i>has made his competitors envious.</i>

10
00:00:52,595 --> 00:00:55,807
<i>He is the youngest chef ever
to achieve a five-star rating.</i>

11
00:00:56,057 --> 00:00:58,184
<i>Chef Gusteau's cookbook,
</i>Anyone Can Cook!

12
00:00:58,267 --> 00:01:00,395
<i>climbed to the top of the bestseller list.</i>

13
00:01:00,478 --> 00:01:02,814
<i>But not everyone
celebrates its success.</i>

14
00:01:02,897 --> 00:01:05,441
<i>Amusing title,</i> Anyone Can Cook!

15
00:01:05,817 --> 00:01:09,570
<i>What's even more amusing is that
Gusteau actually seems to believe it.</i>

16
00:01:09,695 --> 00:01:12,240
<i>I, on the other hand,
take cooking seriously.</i>

17
00:01:12,323 --> 00:01:16,119
<i>And, no, I don't think
anyone can do it.</i>

18
00:01:54,365 --> 00:01:56,367
<i>This is me.</i>

19
00:01:56,701 --> 00:02:00,163
<i>I think it's apparent I need
to rethink my life a little bit.</i>

20
00:02:00,246 --> 00:02:01,873
<i>What's my problem?</i>

21
00:02:01,956 --> 00:02:03,916
<i>First of all, I'm a rat.</i>

22
00:02:05,960 --> 00:02:08,504
<i>Which means life is hard.</i>

23
00:02:09,714 --> 00:02:14,886
<i>And second, I have a highly developed
sense of taste and smell.</i>

24
00:02:15,470 --> 00:02:19,807
Flour, eggs, sugar, vanilla bean...

25
00:02:19,891 --> 00:02:22,101
Oh! Small twist of lemon.

26
00:02:22,185 --> 00:02:25,813
Whoa, you can smell all that?
You have a gift.

27
00:02:25,897 --> 00:02:29,358
<i>This is Emile, my brother.
He's easily impressed.</i>

28
00:02:29,442 --> 00:02:33,070
So you can smell ingredients?
So what?

29
00:02:33,237 --> 00:02:36,240
<i>This is my dad.
He's never impressed.</i>

30
00:02:36,616 --> 00:02:39,577
<i>He also happens to be
the leader of our clan.</i>

31
00:02:39,785 --> 00:02:43,122
<i>So, what's wrong with having
highly developed senses?</i>

32
00:02:43,206 --> 00:02:47,376
- Whoa, whoa, whoa! Don't eat that!
- What's going on here?

33
00:02:47,919 --> 00:02:50,421
<i>Turns out that funny smell
was rat poison.</i>

34
00:02:51,422 --> 00:02:54,842
<i>Suddenly, Dad didn't think
my talent was useless.</i>

35
00:02:54,926 --> 00:02:57,386
<i>I was feeling pretty good
about my gift,</i>

36
00:02:57,470 --> 00:02:59,931
<i>until Dad gave me a job.</i>

37
00:03:00,306 --> 00:03:01,641
Clean.

38
00:03:01,974 --> 00:03:02,975
Clean.

39
00:03:03,100 --> 00:03:04,477
<i>That's right. Poison checker.</i>

40
00:03:04,560 --> 00:03:05,728
Cleanerific.

41
00:03:05,811 --> 00:03:07,313
Cleanerino.

42
00:03:07,772 --> 00:03:09,524
Close to godliness.

43
00:03:10,441 --> 00:03:14,737
Which means clean.
You know, cleanliness is close to...

44
00:03:14,946 --> 00:03:16,697
Never mind. Move on.

45
00:03:17,281 --> 00:03:19,283
<i>Well, it made my dad proud.</i>

46
00:03:19,367 --> 00:03:23,996
Now, don't you feel better, Remy?
You've helped a noble cause.

47
00:03:24,080 --> 00:03:26,666
Noble? We're thieves, Dad.

48
00:03:26,749 --> 00:03:30,378
And what we're stealing is,
let's face it, garbage.

49
00:03:30,461 --> 00:03:32,463
It isn't stealing if no one wants it.

50
00:03:32,547 --> 00:03:35,091
If no one wants it,
why are we stealing it?

51
00:03:35,466 --> 00:03:38,219
<i>Let's just say we have
different points of view.</i>

52
00:03:39,220 --> 00:03:40,721
<i>This much I knew:</i>

53
00:03:40,805 --> 00:03:44,809
<i>If you are what you eat,
then I only want to eat the good stuff.</i>

54
00:03:44,934 --> 00:03:46,394
<i>But to my dad...</i>

55
00:03:46,477 --> 00:03:47,645
Food is fuel.

56
00:03:47,728 --> 00:03:51,399
You get picky about what you put in the tank,
your engine is going to die.

57
00:03:51,482 --> 00:03:53,067
Now shut up and eat your garbage.

58
00:03:53,150 --> 00:03:54,652
Look, if we're going to be thieves,

59
00:03:54,735 --> 00:03:56,612
why not steal the good stuff
in the kitchen,

60
00:03:56,696 --> 00:03:58,322
where nothing is poisoned?

61
00:03:58,406 --> 00:04:00,992
First of all, we are not thieves.

62
00:04:01,075 --> 00:04:03,953
Secondly, stay out of the kitchen
and away from the humans.

63
00:04:04,036 --> 00:04:05,246
It's dangerous.

64
00:04:05,329 --> 00:04:09,250
<i>I know I'm supposed to hate humans,
but there's something about them.</i>

65
00:04:09,333 --> 00:04:13,713
<i>They don't just survive.
They discover, they create.</i>

66
00:04:14,046 --> 00:04:16,257
<i>I mean, just look at what
they do with food.</i>

67
00:04:16,340 --> 00:04:17,842
<i>How can I describe it?</i>

68
00:04:17,925 --> 00:04:21,929
<i>Good food is like music you can taste,
color you can smell.</i>

69
00:04:22,013 --> 00:04:24,473
<i>There is excellence all around you.</i>

70
00:04:24,557 --> 00:04:28,144
<i>You need only be aware
to stop and savor it.</i>

71
00:04:32,023 --> 00:04:34,233
<i>Oh, Gusteau was right.</i>

72
00:04:34,483 --> 00:04:37,069
<i>Oh, yeah.</i>

73
00:04:37,445 --> 00:04:39,071
<i>Oh, amazing.</i>

74
00:04:39,739 --> 00:04:42,950
<i>Each flavor was totally unique.</i>

75
00:04:46,996 --> 00:04:50,207
<i>But combine one flavor with another,</i>

76
00:04:50,291 --> 00:04:53,085
<i>and something new was created.</i>

77
00:04:58,758 --> 00:05:01,302
<i>So now I had a secret life.</i>

78
00:05:09,101 --> 00:05:11,729
<i>The only one who knew
about it was Emile.</i>

79
00:05:11,979 --> 00:05:14,231
Hey, Emile. Emile.

80
00:05:14,523 --> 00:05:16,525
I found a mushroom.

81
00:05:16,609 --> 00:05:19,987
Come on, you're good at hiding food.
Help me find a good place to put this.

82
00:05:20,404 --> 00:05:23,491
<i>He doesn't understand me,
but I can be myself around him.</i>

83
00:05:23,574 --> 00:05:25,326
Why are you walking like that?

84
00:05:25,409 --> 00:05:28,412
I don't want to constantly
have to wash my paws.

85
00:05:28,496 --> 00:05:30,581
Did you ever think about
how we walk on the same paws

86
00:05:30,665 --> 00:05:31,874
that we handle food with?

87
00:05:31,957 --> 00:05:34,043
You ever think about what
we put into our mouths?

88
00:05:34,126 --> 00:05:35,211
All the time.

89
00:05:35,294 --> 00:05:37,880
When I eat, I don't want to taste
everywhere my paws have been.

90
00:05:37,963 --> 00:05:39,131
Well, go ahead.

91
00:05:39,215 --> 00:05:42,968
But if Dad sees you walking like that,
he's not going to like it.

92
00:05:43,052 --> 00:05:44,929
What have you got there?

93
00:05:47,640 --> 00:05:49,392
You found cheese?

94
00:05:49,850 --> 00:05:54,230
And not just any cheese.
Tomme de chèvre de pays!

95
00:05:54,397 --> 00:05:56,899
That would go beautifully
with my mushroom.

96
00:05:56,982 --> 00:05:57,983
And...

97
00:06:00,194 --> 00:06:03,406
This rosemary! This rosemary

98
00:06:03,489 --> 00:06:07,201
with maybe with a few drops
from this sweet grass.

99
00:06:07,618 --> 00:06:10,663
Well, throw it on the pile, I guess,
and then we'll... You know...

100
00:06:10,746 --> 00:06:15,167
We don't want to throw this in
with the garbage. This is special.

101
00:06:15,251 --> 00:06:16,877
But we're supposed
to return to the colony

102
00:06:16,961 --> 00:06:18,546
before sundown or,
you know, Dad's gonna...

103
00:06:18,629 --> 00:06:19,714
Emile!

104
00:06:19,797 --> 00:06:21,716
There are possibilities
unexplored here.

105
00:06:21,799 --> 00:06:23,300
We got to cook this.

106
00:06:23,384 --> 00:06:27,888
Now, exactly how we
cook this is the real...

107
00:06:29,140 --> 00:06:30,141
Yeah.

108
00:06:30,808 --> 00:06:33,060
The key is to keep turning it.

109
00:06:33,144 --> 00:06:37,732
Get the smoky flavor
nice and even.

110
00:06:37,815 --> 00:06:40,025
That storm's getting closer.

111
00:06:40,317 --> 00:06:45,030
Hey, Remy, you think that
maybe we shouldn't be so...

112
00:06:56,834 --> 00:06:58,335
You got to taste this!

113
00:06:58,419 --> 00:07:02,757
This is... It's got this kind of...
It's burny, melty...

114
00:07:02,840 --> 00:07:06,844
It's not really a smoky taste.
It's a certain... It's kind of like a...

115
00:07:06,927 --> 00:07:10,848
It's got, like, this "ba-boom, zap"
kind of taste. Don't you think?

116
00:07:10,931 --> 00:07:14,185
- What would you call that flavor?
- Lightning-y?

117
00:07:14,393 --> 00:07:18,898
Yeah. It's lightning-y!
We got to do that again.

118
00:07:18,981 --> 00:07:21,650
Okay, when the next storm comes,
we'll go up on the roof...

119
00:07:21,734 --> 00:07:25,196
I know what this needs. Saffron.
A little saffron would make this.

120
00:07:25,279 --> 00:07:27,823
Saffron. Why do I get the feeling

121
00:07:27,907 --> 00:07:29,867
- it's in the kitchen?
- It's in the kitchen.

122
00:07:36,749 --> 00:07:38,918
- Saffron.
- Not good.

123
00:07:39,001 --> 00:07:40,461
Saffron.

124
00:07:40,544 --> 00:07:44,465
Don't like it.
She's going to wake up.

125
00:07:44,548 --> 00:07:45,966
I've been down here a million times.

126
00:07:46,050 --> 00:07:49,261
She turns on the cooking channel,
boom, she never wakes up.

127
00:07:49,345 --> 00:07:51,347
You've been here a million times?

128
00:07:51,430 --> 00:07:55,142
I'm telling you, saffron will be just the thing.
Gusteau swears by it.

129
00:07:55,226 --> 00:07:57,061
Okay. Who's Gusteau?

130
00:07:57,144 --> 00:08:00,439
Just the greatest chef in the world.
Wrote this cookbook.

131
00:08:00,523 --> 00:08:03,400
Wait. You read?

132
00:08:03,484 --> 00:08:08,322
- Well, not excessively.
- Oh, man. Does Dad know?

133
00:08:08,405 --> 00:08:12,993
You could fill a book, a lot of books,
with things Dad doesn't know.

134
00:08:13,077 --> 00:08:17,248
And they have, which is why I read.
Which is also our secret.

135
00:08:17,414 --> 00:08:18,833
I don't like secrets.

136
00:08:18,916 --> 00:08:22,753
All this cooking and reading
and TV-watching

137
00:08:22,837 --> 00:08:25,172
while we read and cook.

138
00:08:25,256 --> 00:08:28,342
It's like you're involving me in crime,
and I let you.

139
00:08:28,425 --> 00:08:29,885
Why do I let you?

140
00:08:34,515 --> 00:08:36,600
What's taking those kids so long?

141
00:08:37,643 --> 00:08:40,729
L'Aquila saffron. Italian. Huh?

142
00:08:40,938 --> 00:08:44,525
Gusteau says it's excellent.
Good thing the old lady is a food love...

143
00:08:44,608 --> 00:08:47,319
<i>Forget mystique.
This is about your cooking.</i>

144
00:08:47,403 --> 00:08:49,905
Hey! That's Gusteau. Emile, look.

145
00:08:49,989 --> 00:08:52,533
<i>Great cooking is not
for the faint of heart.</i>

146
00:08:52,616 --> 00:08:55,244
<i>You must be imaginative,
strong hearted.</i>

147
00:08:55,327 --> 00:08:57,413
<i>You must try things
that may not work.</i>

148
00:08:57,496 --> 00:08:59,623
<i>And you must not let anyone
define your limits</i>

149
00:08:59,707 --> 00:09:01,876
<i>because of where you come from.</i>

150
00:09:01,959 --> 00:09:04,211
<i>Your only limit is your soul.</i>

151
00:09:04,295 --> 00:09:11,302
<i>What I say is true. Anyone can cook.
But only the fearless can be great.</i>

152
00:09:11,969 --> 00:09:13,387
Pure poetry.

153
00:09:13,470 --> 00:09:15,514
<i>But it was not to last.</i>

154
00:09:15,890 --> 00:09:18,767
<i>Gusteau's restaurant lost
one of its five stars</i>

155
00:09:18,851 --> 00:09:23,564
<i>after a scathing review by France's
top food critic, Anton Ego.</i>

156
00:09:24,106 --> 00:09:26,233
<i>It was a severe blow to Gusteau,</i>

157
00:09:26,317 --> 00:09:29,403
<i>and the brokenhearted chef
died shortly afterwards,</i>

158
00:09:29,486 --> 00:09:33,616
<i>which, according to tradition,
meant the loss of another star.</i>

159
00:09:33,824 --> 00:09:36,201
Gusteau is dead?

160
00:09:50,382 --> 00:09:51,634
Run!

161
00:09:54,178 --> 00:09:56,305
No, you'll lead her to the colony!

162
00:10:15,199 --> 00:10:18,285
- Help, Remy, help!
- Emile! Start swinging the light!

163
00:10:20,537 --> 00:10:21,997
Try to grab you.

164
00:10:25,417 --> 00:10:27,294
Emile, swing to me.

165
00:11:00,995 --> 00:11:04,456
Evacuate! Everyone, to the boats.

166
00:11:08,502 --> 00:11:11,088
- Let me through!
- The book.

167
00:11:12,297 --> 00:11:14,550
Excuse me. Move, move.

168
00:11:29,773 --> 00:11:32,901
Go, go, go, go.
Move, move, move.

169
00:11:33,777 --> 00:11:36,780
Get the bridge up!
Move it, move it!

170
00:11:37,406 --> 00:11:38,866
Hey, Johnny! Hurry!

171
00:11:39,033 --> 00:11:40,576
Push off. Come on.

172
00:11:41,535 --> 00:11:42,745
Get hold!

173
00:11:46,457 --> 00:11:49,376
- Take the baby. Here!
- Give me your paw.

174
00:11:50,377 --> 00:11:52,004
Hey, wait for me!

175
00:11:56,925 --> 00:11:59,053
Is everybody here?
Do we have everybody?

176
00:11:59,136 --> 00:12:01,764
- Wait a minute. Where's Remy?
- Right here. I'm coming.

177
00:12:02,306 --> 00:12:03,640
I'm coming!

178
00:12:04,475 --> 00:12:07,519
Hold on, Son.
Give him something to grab on to.

179
00:12:07,644 --> 00:12:09,688
Come on, boy. Paddle, Son.

180
00:12:09,772 --> 00:12:11,732
Come on. Reach for it.

181
00:12:12,649 --> 00:12:13,901
You can do it.

182
00:12:18,030 --> 00:12:19,573
- Remy!
- Dad!

183
00:12:19,656 --> 00:12:22,409
Come on. You can make it.
You can make it.

184
00:12:28,373 --> 00:12:30,334
Guys, wait. Stop!

185
00:12:30,417 --> 00:12:32,503
Remy. Come on. Paddle.

186
00:12:32,586 --> 00:12:36,298
Hold on! Wait for me. Hold on.

187
00:12:38,884 --> 00:12:40,177
Dad?

188
00:12:43,305 --> 00:12:44,306
Dad?

189
00:12:55,109 --> 00:12:56,652
Which way?

190
00:13:47,119 --> 00:13:48,579
<i>I waited</i>

191
00:13:50,998 --> 00:13:52,499
<i>for a sound,</i>

192
00:13:54,877 --> 00:13:56,420
<i>a voice,</i>

193
00:13:58,589 --> 00:14:00,174
<i>a sign,</i>

194
00:14:02,551 --> 00:14:04,011
<i>something.</i>

195
00:14:22,821 --> 00:14:26,617
If you are hungry,
go up and look around, Remy.

196
00:14:28,869 --> 00:14:30,954
Why do you wait and mope?

197
00:14:31,371 --> 00:14:35,667
Well, I've just lost my family,
all my friends,

198
00:14:36,793 --> 00:14:38,295
probably forever.

199
00:14:38,712 --> 00:14:41,465
- How do you know?
- Well, I...

200
00:14:42,132 --> 00:14:45,886
You are an illustration.
Why am I talking to you?

201
00:14:46,053 --> 00:14:50,766
Well, you just lost your family,
all your friends. You are lonely.

202
00:14:50,849 --> 00:14:53,060
Yeah. Well, you're dead.

203
00:14:53,143 --> 00:14:56,521
Ah, but that is no match
for wishful thinking.

204
00:14:56,605 --> 00:14:58,357
If you focus on what
you've left behind,

205
00:14:58,440 --> 00:15:00,817
you'll never be able to see
what lies ahead.

206
00:15:00,901 --> 00:15:03,153
Now go up and look around.

207
00:15:40,232 --> 00:15:41,441
Champagne!

208
00:15:42,818 --> 00:15:44,278
What are you doing?

209
00:15:45,112 --> 00:15:46,280
I'm hungry.

210
00:15:46,446 --> 00:15:47,864
I don't know where I am,

211
00:15:47,948 --> 00:15:49,658
and I don't know when
I'll find food again.

212
00:15:49,741 --> 00:15:53,370
Remy, you are better than that.
You are a cook.

213
00:15:53,537 --> 00:15:58,500
A cook makes. A thief takes.
You are not a thief.

214
00:15:59,126 --> 00:16:00,836
But I am hungry.

215
00:16:02,504 --> 00:16:04,172
Food will come, Remy.

216
00:16:04,256 --> 00:16:08,885
Food always comes to those
who love to cook.

217
00:16:20,897 --> 00:16:24,234
- You think I am playing?
- You don't have the guts.

218
00:17:10,614 --> 00:17:11,782
Paris?

219
00:17:12,366 --> 00:17:15,911
All this time I've been
underneath Paris?

220
00:17:17,954 --> 00:17:19,206
Wow.

221
00:17:21,875 --> 00:17:23,627
It's beautiful.

222
00:17:24,795 --> 00:17:27,422
The most beautiful.

223
00:17:27,714 --> 00:17:30,342
Gusteau's? Your restaurant?

224
00:17:30,425 --> 00:17:32,886
You've led me to your restaurant.

225
00:17:33,929 --> 00:17:39,142
It seems as though I have. Yes.
There it is. I have led you to it.

226
00:17:39,226 --> 00:17:40,644
I got to see this.

227
00:17:41,269 --> 00:17:42,854
- Ready to go on table seven.
- Coming around.

228
00:17:42,938 --> 00:17:44,648
- One order of steamed pike up.
- Coming up.

229
00:17:44,731 --> 00:17:46,483
I need more soup bowls, please.

230
00:17:46,566 --> 00:17:49,194
I need two rack of lamb.
I need more leeks.

231
00:17:49,277 --> 00:17:52,572
I need two salmon,
three salade composée, and three fillet.

232
00:17:52,656 --> 00:17:54,574
Three orders of salade
composée working.

233
00:17:54,658 --> 00:17:56,368
Firing two orders, seared salmon.

234
00:17:56,451 --> 00:17:58,995
Three fillet working. I need plates.

235
00:17:59,079 --> 00:18:01,748
- Fire seven.
- Three salade composée up.

236
00:18:01,832 --> 00:18:03,792
Don't mess with my mise!

237
00:18:04,000 --> 00:18:05,085
Open down low.

238
00:18:05,168 --> 00:18:08,171
I'm getting buried here.

239
00:18:08,296 --> 00:18:11,007
Hello, Chef Skinner.
How your night be now?

240
00:18:11,091 --> 00:18:13,135
- <i>Bonjour</i>, chef.
- Hello, Chef Skinner.

241
00:18:13,218 --> 00:18:15,762
- Evening, chef.
- Ordering <i>deux</i> fillet.

242
00:18:15,846 --> 00:18:17,722
Hey, boss, look who is here.

243
00:18:17,806 --> 00:18:20,225
Alfredo Linguini, Renata's little boy.

244
00:18:20,308 --> 00:18:21,935
- Hi.
- All grown up, eh?

245
00:18:22,018 --> 00:18:25,230
You remember Renata,
Gusteau's old flame?

246
00:18:25,856 --> 00:18:29,025
- Yes. How are you...
- Linguini.

247
00:18:29,109 --> 00:18:33,321
Yes, Linguini. So nice of you to visit.
How is...

248
00:18:33,405 --> 00:18:35,282
- My mother?
- Renata.

249
00:18:35,365 --> 00:18:38,201
- Yes, Renata. How is she?
- Good.

250
00:18:38,493 --> 00:18:41,913
Well, not...
